HDFS basics:¶

HDFS is the hadoop distributed file system which is written in java and it is based on google file system GFS. it lies on top of a native file system such as ext3 or ext4.
In the cluster, there will be a NameNode which stores meta-data of data blocks, and DataNodes which contain the actual data blocks. For the sake of fault tolerance, HDFS stores redundant copies of each data block (by default = 3).

Storing and retreiving files in HDFS:¶

Files are split into 128 MB blocks by default and each block is replicated in multipe data nodes.

HDFS best practices:¶

It is recommended that HDFS repository is organized carefully and you define a standrd structure for your directory. For example:  
/user – data of a single user
/tmp – Temporary data shared between multiple users.
/etl – Work in progress in a stage of etl.

Command Line access to HDFS:¶

FsShell commands [$ hdfs dfs]:¶

In the VM terminal, you can use commands like the following:

Function Command
Copy file1.txt from local directory to hfds \$ hdfs dfs -put file1.txt /dir/file1.txt
Copy file to local directory dir andchange name to file2.txt \$ hdfs dfs -get /dir/file1.txt file2.txt
Create directory dire1 \$ hdfs dfs -mkdir dire1
Delete directory dire1 \$ hdfs dfs -rm -r dire1
List UP file in a directory dir \$ hdfs dfs -ls /dir
List up the files in hdfs root directory \$ hdfs dfs -ls /
display content in file file1.txt \$ hdfs dfs -cat /dir/file1.txt

Note: In HDFS, relative paths are relative to the home directory in our case /user/hadoop/.

Task 2¶

Task 2.1: Running Hadoop MapReduce (word count example):¶

To run this example, you need to extract the zip file attached with the assignment file on Moodle.

1.In your local directory /home/bitnami, create a folder called Labs and then subfolder Lab1. Move the downloaded zip file to Lab1 and then extract it.

In this task, we are going to run a simple example that count words frequency using Hadoop MapReduce.
We will start by using hdfs commands to create a directory for our input.

  1. create a directory with name "hdfslab2":
    hdfs dfs -mkdir hdfsLab1

  2. Create a subdirectory "input":
    hdfs dfs -mkdir hdfsLab1/input

  3. Change the local directroy to "Labs/Lab1":
    cd /home/bitnami/Labs/Lab1/

  4. Move the file "AliceInWonderLandPart1.txt", in the extracted folder, to the hdfs cluster:
    hdfs dfs -put /home/bitnami/Labs/Lab1/AliceInWonderLandPart1.txt /user/hadoop/hdfsLab1/input

  5. Now it is time to run our first MapReduce example "wordcount" using the following command:
    hadoop jar /home/bitnami/Labs/Lab1/WordCount.jar ee.ut.cs.dsg.bigdatamanagement.WordCount /home/bitnami/hdfsLab1/input /user/hadoop/hdfsLab1/output
